definition.value: Molecular entities containing an as-indacene skeleton.
A C-nitro compound that is a hydrocarbon in which one or more of the hydrogens has been replaced by nitro groups.
A nitroalkene having ethenyl as the alkene portion.
A nitrohydrocarbon that consists of an arene skeleton substituted by one or more nitro groups at unspecified positions.
An acrylic macromolecule, composed of acrylic acid repeating units.
A homopolymer macromolecule prepared from acrylic acid or a derivative of acrylic acid.
A macromolecule composed of repeating 1-carbamoylethylene units.

A dibenzoazepine (specifically 1,2,3,4,10,14b-hexahydrodibenzo[c,f]pyrazino[1,2-a]azepine) methyl-substituted on N-2. Closely related to (and now mostly superseded by) the tetracyclic antidepressant mirtazapinean, it is an atypical antidepressant used in the treatment of depression throughout Europe and elsewhere.
An amino group formed by replacement of two of the hydrogen atoms in ammonia by groups or atoms other than hydrogen atoms.
An amino group formed by replacement of all three of the hydrogen atoms in ammonia by a groups or atoms other than hydrogen atoms.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate of the dihydrochloride salt of pramiprexole.
A hydrochloride that is the anhydrous dihydrochloride salt of pramipexole.
Any member of the class of  xanthenes based on a xanthone skeleton.
The simplest member of the class of  monofluorobenzenes that is benzene carrying a single fluoro substituent.
A compound in which an anionic site Y(-) is attached directly to a heteroatom X(+) (usually nitrogen, phosphorus or sulfur) carrying a formal positive charge.

An  organic molecule that is electrically neutral carrying a positive and a negative charge in one of its major canonical descriptions. In most dipolar compounds the charges are delocalized; however the term is also applied to species where this is not the case.
A compound where a formally positive nitrogen atom is bound to a formally negative atom (carbon or other atom).
A compound where a formally positive phosphorus atom is bound to a formally negative carbon atom.
Compounds having the structure R3P(+)-C(-)R2 <-> R3P=CR2, where the phosphorus atom is bonded to four separate atoms.
A compound where a formally positive oxygen atom is bound to a formally negative atom.
A compound where a formally positive sulfur atom is bound to a formally negative carbon atom.
A 1,2-dipolar compound of general structure R3N(+)-C(-)R2.
A 1,3-dipolar compound having the structure R2C(-)-N(+)(R)=CR2 <-> R2C=N(+)(R)-C(-)R2.
A 1,3-dipolar compound having the structure: R2C=O(+)-C(-)R2 <-> R2C(+)-O-C(-)R2.

Any oxygen ylide that is a compound having the structure R2O(+)-C(-)-R2. 2. Any of the class of 1,3-dipolar compounds of general structure R2C=O(+)-Y(-), comprising carbonyl imides, carbonyl oxides and carbonyl ylides.
A 1,3-dipolar compound having the structure: R2C=O(+)-N(-)-R <-> R2C(+)-O-N(-)-R.
A 1,3-dipolar compound having the structure: R2C(-)-O(+)=O <-> R2C=O(+)-O(-).
A role played by a phosphonium ylide in a Wittig reaction.
A macromolecule molecule with a silsesquioxane repeating unit.
A silsesquioxane that is a polycyclic cage of empirical formula [HSiO1.5]n.

A silsesquioxane cage consisting of two ten-membered rings of alternating silicon and oxygen atoms, with each silicon atom in one ring joined to a silicon in the second ring by a bridging oxygen atom and with a hydrogen atom attached to all ten silicon atoms.
The (1S,2R)-(+)-diastereoisomer of propoxyphene.
A compound containing at least one carbon-aluminium bond.
